WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.940
So I will be discussing now targeting calreticulin and MPNs.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:06.480
These are my disclosures.

00:00:07.100 --> 00:00:10.580
So calreticulin, quick update, a quick background.

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:15.220
It is mutated in 20% to 30% of patients with ET and myelofibrosis.

00:00:16.400 --> 00:00:20.380
Calreticulin protein is a protein that's present in the endoplasmic reticulum,

00:00:20.840 --> 00:00:22.400
and it's a calcium-binding protein.

00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:25.580
It acts as a chaperone, so assists in proper folding of proteins,

00:00:26.220 --> 00:00:30.500
has a role in calcium homeostasis, and immune-mediated cell death.

00:00:30.780 --> 00:00:31.680
It has three domains.

00:00:31.820 --> 00:00:36.100
We have the N-terminus, we have the P-domain, and we have the C-terminus.

00:00:36.280 --> 00:00:41.680
And if you look at the C-terminus, it has a four-immunoacid area called the K-del area.

00:00:41.860 --> 00:00:45.240
That's the area that leads to the localization to the endoplasmic reticulum.

00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:50.920
So if I take this K-del area out, the protein will leave the endoplasmic reticulum.

00:00:51.920 --> 00:00:55.620
So mutations in calreticulin, two most common mutations,

00:00:55.780 --> 00:00:56.200
type 1 and type 2.

00:00:56.380 --> 00:00:58.320
Type 1 is 52-base-pair deletion.

00:00:58.760 --> 00:01:00.460
Type 1 is 52-base-pair deletion.

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:02.160
Type 2 is 5-base-pair insertion.

00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:06.280
And we have additional in-between what we call type 1 and type 2-like mutations.

00:01:06.740 --> 00:01:10.620
And all of these mutations lead to a novel C-terminus lacking the K-del motif.

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:15.240
So it leads to the new C-terminus area.

00:01:15.800 --> 00:01:20.280
And if you lost the K-del motif, the calreticulin is secreted to the cell surface,

00:01:20.680 --> 00:01:24.620
acts as a paracrine hormone, and activates the MIPL or T-po receptor,

00:01:24.620 --> 00:01:26.120
and activates the JAK.

00:01:26.220 --> 00:01:26.800
That pathway.

00:01:28.980 --> 00:01:33.640
And this mutant color protein, you can detect it in plasma from patients

00:01:33.640 --> 00:01:36.800
with color-mutating MPNs, but you don't see that with patients

00:01:36.800 --> 00:01:38.300
with JAK2 mutations, for example.

00:01:41.220 --> 00:01:43.120
So targeting mutant color.

00:01:43.260 --> 00:01:46.740
So this is a neoantigen coming to the cell surface.

00:01:46.900 --> 00:01:48.260
It's a neoantigen.

00:01:48.480 --> 00:01:52.400
So you can target it by vaccines, target it by antibodies,

00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:56.080
or cellular therapy with bispecific or CAR-T therapy.

00:01:56.220 --> 00:01:58.560
So vaccines, we have three vaccines.

00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:02.720
Two of them are published already in ET and MF, but unfortunately,

00:02:02.720 --> 00:02:04.600
those two vaccines did not pan out.

00:02:04.600 --> 00:02:07.600
They were poorly immunogenic, no clinical or molecular responses.

00:02:07.600 --> 00:02:12.120
The third vaccine is under study at Mount Sinai, no reported results yet.

00:02:12.440 --> 00:02:15.980
But when you see the results from the first two vaccines, you ask yourself,

00:02:16.220 --> 00:02:18.200
what about T-cell exhaustion and MPNs?

00:02:18.200 --> 00:02:20.720
Maybe that's why they are poorly immunogenic.

00:02:22.020 --> 00:02:24.120
What about antibody modality?

00:02:24.120 --> 00:02:25.480
We have INSIGHT-A.

00:02:25.480 --> 00:02:25.980
INSIGHT-A, 3.0.

00:02:25.980 --> 00:02:27.480
INSIGHT-A, 3.3.989.

00:02:27.480 --> 00:02:29.160
I'll call it 9.8.9 antibody.

00:02:29.740 --> 00:02:35.400
This is a fully human IgG1 monoclonal antibody that selectively target the mutant calreticline

00:02:35.400 --> 00:02:40.540
because of the new C-terminus.

00:02:41.160 --> 00:02:44.100
There are two ongoing phase one studies in patients with ET and MF.

00:02:44.700 --> 00:02:49.600
So one each in the US and the others are global outside of the US.

00:02:49.820 --> 00:02:54.020
For ET patients, it has to be high risk patients with resistance or intolerance

00:02:54.020 --> 00:02:55.740
to previous cytoreductive therapy.

00:02:55.740 --> 00:03:02.600
In MF, patients have to be intolerant, resistant, or ineligible for JAK inhibitor.

00:03:02.860 --> 00:03:09.460
And then later, an arm for patients who were treatment naive, first line randomized

00:03:09.460 --> 00:03:13.280
between the antibody plus/minus ruxolitinib was open.

00:03:13.280 --> 00:03:18.760
This is an intravenous antibody, and it was a dose escalation phase one.

00:03:18.760 --> 00:03:25.500
It started at 24 milligram up to 2,500 milligram, and no dose-limiting toxicities were noted.

00:03:25.500 --> 00:03:29.520
So this is the ET study, 55 patients.

00:03:29.520 --> 00:03:33.020
You'll see more type one rather than type two, which what we see in practice.

00:03:33.840 --> 00:03:40.300
And when you look at the adverse events, overall, 93% of patients still receiving treatment

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:44.380
at the time of the data cut point for the presentation at ASH.

00:03:44.840 --> 00:03:48.560
Four patients discontinued treatment, and you look at the most common adverse events, fatigue,

00:03:48.560 --> 00:03:50.260
headache, upper respiratory tract infection.

00:03:50.260 --> 00:03:55.260
Grade three adverse events, you will see cytopenias, neutropenia, and anemia, but it was,

00:03:55.260 --> 00:03:59.880
was mainly in patients who were already on, like concurrently or just were on hydria, like

00:03:59.880 --> 00:04:01.320
just stopped hydria.

00:04:01.320 --> 00:04:06.820
Interestingly, we did not see grade three thrombocytopenia, although these patients,

00:04:06.820 --> 00:04:10.660
for example, have high platelet count, and then you're bringing these platelets to normal,

00:04:10.660 --> 00:04:14.040
but they don't go much below normal.

00:04:14.040 --> 00:04:15.080
So that was interesting.

00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:20.980
Some patients had lipase and amylase elevation, and those were like intermittent transient

00:04:20.980 --> 00:04:24.700
without pancreatitis, clinical pancreatitis.

00:04:24.700 --> 00:04:25.020
So this is the results.

00:04:25.020 --> 00:04:27.420
This is the data about the platelet control.

00:04:27.420 --> 00:04:32.080
You will see in patients who had the higher doses, 400 to 2,500, there was more consistent

00:04:32.080 --> 00:04:35.740
normalization of the platelet count.

00:04:35.740 --> 00:04:40.020
And this is a plot showing that the complete hematologic response, means normalization

00:04:40.020 --> 00:04:44.340
of the platelet count, was seen in 83%, and that was durable, means more than 12 weeks

00:04:44.340 --> 00:04:48.240
in 46% of patients.

00:04:48.240 --> 00:04:54.780
We saw molecular responses, according to the IWG criteria, like VF decrease more than 50%,

00:04:54.780 --> 00:04:57.840
and around 30% of patients.

00:04:57.840 --> 00:05:02.700
And you can see also the abnormal megakaryocytes in the marrow, the color technically mutated,

00:05:02.700 --> 00:05:08.360
were decreased and would increase the color non-mutated megakaryocytes.

00:05:08.360 --> 00:05:14.040
So it seems these unmutated megakaryocytes were just sitting there with suppressed and

00:05:14.040 --> 00:05:19.580
just increased after treatment, and this is maybe why we did not see grade three thrombocytopenia.

00:05:19.580 --> 00:05:20.580
What about the MF?

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:22.540
We have 52 patients treated.

00:05:22.540 --> 00:05:24.540
Here you will see more cytopenias than the ETM.

00:05:24.540 --> 00:05:31.420
You will see more MF than the ET population, and there were also increased AST and ALTs

00:05:31.420 --> 00:05:38.060
noted in 10 patients.

00:05:38.060 --> 00:05:45.580
We saw fatigue, we saw arthralgias, we talked about the AST increase, but in general, 86%

00:05:45.580 --> 00:05:49.600
of patients still receiving therapy at the time of the cut point.

00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:50.600
What about the responses?

00:05:50.600 --> 00:05:54.300
You will see treatment responses, and around 30%, they had the spenic volume reduction,

00:05:54.300 --> 00:06:07.800
33% more than 35%, also around 39% had symptom improvement, like more than 50% reduction

00:06:07.800 --> 00:06:10.880
in the MPN-SAF form.

00:06:10.880 --> 00:06:14.460
Patients who were treatment naive had higher responses in the spleen volume reduction and

00:06:14.460 --> 00:06:17.840
higher percentage of symptom improvement.

00:06:17.840 --> 00:06:21.540
What also was interesting, we saw anemia responses, like in patients who were anemic, you will

00:06:21.540 --> 00:06:24.060
see anemia responses.

00:06:24.060 --> 00:06:30.560
We saw molecular responses, but it was less pronounced when you compare it to the ET cohort.

00:06:30.560 --> 00:06:35.080
We will see over time if this will deepen or not.

00:06:35.080 --> 00:06:38.380
Future directions, so the same antibody will have a subcutaneous formulation.

00:06:38.380 --> 00:06:44.680
There are two Bispecific in clinical trials, targeting mutant calortecin, binding

00:06:44.680 --> 00:06:50.580
mutant calortecin to CD3, Janssen bispecific and Insight bispecific.

00:06:50.580 --> 00:06:53.820
There is a CAR-T preclinical model and antibody drug conjugate preclinical.

00:06:53.820 --> 00:06:55.980
And thank you.
